snippet.title: "Black Mass Red Carpet" with Johnny Depp, Amber Heard and Dakota Johnson
snippet.description:
Things got a little crazy at the world premiere of Johnny Depp's new gangster film, Black Mass, as he hit the red carpet with wife Amber Heard and Dakota Johnson.

Johnny Depp-starrer ‚ÄúBlack Mass‚Äù world-premiered to positive response Friday at the Venice Film Festival where a relaxed Depp held court, musing on the challenges of playing Boston gangster James ‚ÄúWhitey‚Äù Bulger naturalistically, including a dramatically receding hairline, and how he feels risky physical transformations are part of his duty to give audiences ‚Äúsomething new each time.‚Äù Director Scott Cooper‚Äôs biopic of Bulger, who became an FBI informant and used this status to eliminate criminal competition during the 1970s, ‚Äô80s and early ‚Äô90s, was greeted with applause at the Venice press screening and the press conference was packed to the rafters.

Depp downplayed the purely criminal component of Bulger, whom he described as an man of ‚Äúvery proud Irish immigrant stock, who was loyal to his neighborhood.‚Äù

snippet.title: Social & Criminal Justice Reform with Steve DeAngelo, Amber Moore, Albert Tio & Steve Rolles
snippet.description:
Enjoy exclusive access to the panel discussion between Steve DeAngelo, Amber Moore, Albert Tio, and Steve Rolles which took place at Cannabis Europa during Prohibition Partners LIVE, June 2020.

Building new cannabis laws also means looking to the past and seeking to repair ‚Äî in so far as any of this can be repaired ‚Äî the damage done to communities by previous prohibitionist regulatory frameworks.

The final Cannabis Europa talk of the day came in the form of a panel session on this topic, titled Social & Criminal Justice Reform, where numerous panelists including ‚ÄòFather of the Cannabis Industry‚Äô Steve DeAngelo (Chairman & Co-Founder, Harborside Inc), Albert Tio (President of the Catalonian Cannabis Clubs) and Amber Moore (Senior Researcher, Conservative Drug Policy Reform Group) came together to analyse the role the social and criminal justice system should play in the context of future cannabis law reform.

If you're looking to explore how to enter the cannabis market or how to operate within the international cannabis sector, make sure to secure your place at our next virtual event.

The next Prohibition Partners LIVE event takes place from 17-20th November. 

Super Early Bird tickets are now on sale. Secure your place here: https://prohibitionpartners.live/tickets/

#PPLIVE #CannabisEuropa #SteveDeAngelo #AmberMoore #SteveRolles #Cannabis #CannabisEvent #VirtualConference #ProhibitionPartnersLive #CBD

snippet.title: Amber Heard is the Problem not Johnny Depp
snippet.description:
A judge has granted Johnny Depp access to his ex-wife Amber Heard's phone, which he claims will show she lied about injuries he allegedly caused her.

The "Pirates of the Caribbean" star, who is suing Heard for $50 million in libel, alleges she doctored images purporting to depict her with two black eyes, which she claims she sustained at the hands of the actor in 2015.

"Ms. Heard's counsel has frequently presented these false images during deposition," Depp's lawyer Benjamin Chew said in a court filing to the Circuit Court of Fairfax County, Va.

Depp, 58, is suing Heard, 35, in Virginia for an op-ed she penned in the Washington Post in 2019 about domestic abuse ‚Äî but which he says was a defamatory assault on him.

snippet.localized.title: Amber Heard is the Problem not Johnny Depp
snippet.localized.description:
A judge has granted Johnny Depp access to his ex-wife Amber Heard's phone, which he claims will show she lied about injuries he allegedly caused her.

The "Pirates of the Caribbean" star, who is suing Heard for $50 million in libel, alleges she doctored images purporting to depict her with two black eyes, which she claims she sustained at the hands of the actor in 2015.

"Ms. Heard's counsel has frequently presented these false images during deposition," Depp's lawyer Benjamin Chew said in a court filing to the Circuit Court of Fairfax County, Va.

Depp, 58, is suing Heard, 35, in Virginia for an op-ed she penned in the Washington Post in 2019 about domestic abuse ‚Äî but which he says was a defamatory assault on him.

#AmberHeard #JohnnyDepp #CelebDelux
